{"key":"post-11536596","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11536596</id>\n<content>Quickly rising pressure doesn't harm jars.&amp;nbsp; They're built to withstand vacuum, or in other words a higher pressure outside the jar than inside.&amp;nbsp; I've put the stove on high to heat up the PC for decades without breaking jars.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;One other thing that will break them is packing too tight where they're pressed up against each other.&amp;nbsp; The jars expand slightly when hot, so if they're tight to begin with, they break.&amp;nbsp; However, in this case, he released pressure, thus he had 15 psi in the jars and 0 psi outside the jars.&amp;nbsp; That's a recipe for breaking nearly every time, and the fact that the bottoms broke off confirms this.&amp;nbsp; That's the weakest part of the jar, and they're designed to have the bottoms break off rather than blowing out the side of the jar.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11536937</next>\n<prev>11536557</prev>\n<first>11534089</first>\n<last>11537622</last>\n<when>1259343225</when>\n<utime>11/27/09 07:33 PM</utime>\n</post>"}